rtificates-february-2019/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Colorado, and Michigan.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.colorado.gov/pacific/cdphe/birth-certificates |title=Birth Certificates |website=Colorado Department of Public Health & Environment |access-date=April 29, 2021 |archive-date=November 12, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201112033044/https://www.colorado.gov/pacific/cdphe/birth-certificates |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="leginfo.legislature.ca.gov">{{cite web|title=California Senate Bill "SB-179 Gender identity: female, male, or nonbinary" to enact the Gender Recognition Act, to authorize the change of gender on the new birth certificate to be female, male, or nonbinary.|url=https://leginfo.legislature.ca.gov/faces/billNavClient.xhtml?bill_id=201720180SB179|website=California Legislative Information|access-date=May 25, 2017|date=January 24, 2017|archive-date=June 16, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170616164149/https://leginfo.legislature.ca.gov/faces/billNavClient.xhtml?bill_id=201720180SB179|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="nbcnews.com">{{cite web|last1=O'Hara|first1=Mary Emily|title=Californian Becomes Second US Citizen Granted 'Non-Binary' Gender Status|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/feature/nbc-out/californian-becomes-second-us-citizen-granted-non-binary-gender-status-n654611|website=[[NBC News]]|access-date=September 26, 2016|date=September 26, 2016|archive-date=September 26, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160926204210/https://www.nbcnews.com/feature/nbc-out/californian-becomes-second-us-citizen-granted-non-binary-gender-status-n654611|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="ohara2016">{{cite web| last = O'Hara| first = Mary Emily| title = Nation's First Known Intersex Birth Certificate Issued in NYC| website = [[NBC News]]| access-date = 2016-12-30| date = December 29, 2016| url = https://www.nbcnews.com/feature/nbc-out/nation-s-first-known-intersex-birth-certificate-issued-nyc-n701186| archive-date = 2019-05-09